# Verifier Fanout And Attestations

Verifier packets bind a staged payload hash, manifest hash, condition file hash,
and response schema. A verifier response is useful only when it is about the
same staged hash.

## Verdict Semantics

- `pass`: governed surface exists and was inspected successfully.
- `not_applicable`: no governed surface exists in this payload.
- `fail`: the condition is violated.
- `unknown`: the verifier could not determine the result.

Authorization permits spawning or contacting verifiers. Authorization is never
per-cell evidence.

## Provenance

Record the actual verifier agent, runtime, model, separate-context status, and
message or transcript reference. Preserve dissent. If shared judgment cells
disagree, hold the commit for adjudication instead of selecting the convenient
verdict.

## Effort Tiers

Set verifier model and reasoning effort explicitly when spawning or relaying a
packet. Do not rely on runtime defaults. Judgment-cell verifiers use `high` for
`dry`, `anti-reward-hacking`, `scope-control`, `security-boundaries`, and
`definition-of-done`. Mechanical-cell verifiers use `medium` for payload-scope
checks, clearly not-governed conditions, lookup work, and inventory work.
Medium-tier verifiers may return an escalation verdict when a cell needs the
high-effort judgment lane.

Record each pane's model and effort in dispatch notes. Adjust a running pane
only between rounds, never mid-verification. For long mechanical phases,
respawn at the right tier instead of spending critical-path `xhigh` capacity on
lookups.

## Seals And Attestations

A seal is a Burpvalve attestation. Passing attestations live under
`backpressure/attestations/`. They bind the payload hash and verifier evidence.
Stage only the attestation requested by the gate; do not sweep unrelated
generated files into the commit.
